    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that, that makes more sense. so just to be sure, if there's a dispute over something like a repair that wasn't done, does the escrow agent just hold onto the money until it's settled?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that's correct. If there's a dispute over something like a repair that wasn't completed as agreed upon, the escrow agent will hold onto the funds until the issue is resolved. The escrow agreement typically outlines the conditions under which the funds will be released, and it may include provisions for handling disputes.\n\nIn the event of a disagreement, the parties involved can often work through the issue with the help of their real estate agents, attorneys, or other mediators. If the dispute cannot be resolved amicably, it may need to be settled in court or through arbitration, depending on the terms of the escrow agreement and the nature of the dispute.\n\nDuring this time, the escrow agent will not release the funds to the seller until the dispute is resolved and the terms of the sale are fully satisfied. This ensures that the buyer's interests are protected and that the seller is not unfairly deprived of the funds due to unresolved issues. Once the dispute is settled, the escrow agent will release the funds to the seller, and the buyer will receive their portion of the sale proceeds.\n\nIt's important to note that the specific procedures and requirements for handling disputes can vary depending on the escrow agreement and the laws of the jurisdiction in which the transaction takes place. It's always a good idea",
      "source": "target",
      "gen_token_ids": [
        13022,
        11,
